TY  - JOUR
AU  - Menchik, Paul L.
T1  - Primogeniture, Equal Sharing, and the U.S. Distribution of Wealth*
PY  - 1980
Y1  - 1980/03/01
DO  - 10.2307/1884542
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 94
IS  - 2
SP  - 299
EP  - 316
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - Bequest patterns to children are important in intergenerational models of the distribution of income and wealth. Economies that feature primogeniture will have a greater degree of inequality than those featuring equal division. This paper presents evidence on estate division among children by sex, birth order, family size, estate size, and asset composition. The results presented here are preference-generated not tax-induced due to the tax characteristics within the sampling region. It is shown that equal sharing among children is the rule, a result that casts doubt upon the “altruist” model of inheritance as advanced by Becker and Tomes.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/1884542
ER  - 



